@6732=~Miscellaneous Books and Notes~
@6733=~This assortment of history tomes and letters describe local incidents and matters of concern to the Harper cell here. This collected literature covers east to the High Moor, south to Baldur's Gate, and as north as Daggerford. The Harpers obviously have a lot of vested interest in the region. While local criminal organizations and other political groups vying for dominance of the region would likely find a lot of value in this literature, it has little use to you.~
@6734=~Time of Troubles - Doom of Assassins~
@6735=~Eleasis 13 1358 DR

Bane and Myrkul prepared for an assault on the city of Tantras, in which the god Torm guarded over one of the Tablets of Fate with his most valorous disciplines. As the forces of Zhentil Keep marched towards the city on the coast of the Dragon Reach, Bane and Myrkul devised a terrible plan. Nearby, a great golem made of black glass, forged in the Hells themselves and called the Black Brother, had been planted by Bane long ago. Through ancient ritual it could be animated and inhabited by Bane's Avatar, and with its awesome power he could destroy the city and its guardians, including Torm himself, and take back the Tablet of Fate. 

However, to empower the golem required an immense well of souls to draw from, souls of darkness that aligned with Bane's own evil. It so happened that Bane had a ready well of such a souls to draw from. Nearby, Myrkul's dark priests prepared a spell of death on a mass-scale, perhaps the greatest of such spells ever conceived. Through means unknown, Bane and Myrkul had obtained the True Names of all assassins of Faerûn. Knowing their true names, the spell of mass death killed every assassin while Bane's own priests performed the Stealing of Souls ritual to harness their dark life force and channel it into the Black Brother. And so Bane rose with terrible power, and his ensuing battle with Torm remains perhaps the most remarkable of the Time of Troubles.

One less remarked on matter of this incident was how the death of so many assassins directly undermined Bhaal's own power on Faerûn. As the god of murder and assassinations, the rituals eliminated nearly every true follower of Bhaal through the realms, and rendered Bhaal's avatar a hollow shell of the power he once was, a power so easily dispatched by Cyric the mortal.~
@6736=~Mission Report: Temple Raid~
@6737=~Sir,

I report to inform you that the mission was a success. We breached into the temple swiftly, dispatching the guards without a sound in the night. It appears that our information was correct. We found them gathering the children in pens, like chattel to slaughter. Children of dark heritage they may have been, but innocent all the same. We rushed to save all the children we could.

The ensuing melee was chaos, yet the ambush was well prepared and we fell upon the cultists and cut through them like Selune's light cutting through dark. We were able to fell most of their order without too many losses on our own side, however I regret to inform that Arryn and Pearla were casualties of the battle. A few other injured, but they will recover. 

The chaos allowed the children to flee. This proved a double edged blade. While they are no longer in imminent danger, we have been unable to locate most. We will return with those we were able to secure shortly. We must call our scouts to find the others as soon as possible, I worry what might happen if they fall into the wrong hands.~
@6738=~Ecological Report: Winding Water~
@6739=~After much testing, it seems that the Winding Water may be irrevocably tainted by the dark god's blood. The effects have proved subtle, yet noticeable by the druidic sects surrounding the river. The water itself runs darker than usual. Animals generally refuse to drink from it, and plants that grow nearby do so in twisted brambles. While we've found that the water is not immediately toxic to drink, in large quantities it will cause sickness and eventually death. Several Talonites have been found to be experimenting with the waters, no doubt trying to create more wicked poisons from its contamination. 

A number of druids are doing what they can to cleanse the waters, but this work is expected to take years, if not generations. There has been one other curious matter of note... those rare cultists of Bhaal that still exist seem to draw some divine power from the waters themselves. Perhaps some essence of Bhaal's divinity still exists within the river.

*Note: It has been tested that the divine residue contained within the waters extends only as far out as half a day's travel on horseback. However, I theorize a higher concentration of the taint within the water might be able to be carried out, and perhaps that could provide a direct link back to the source.~
