@6744=~Memo on Known Bhaalspawn~
@6745=~We've attempted to track what Bhaalspawn we can but those efforts have proven difficult. That difficulty is of course complicated by our the need for secrecy within our own organization. Remember that Bhaalspawn pose a unique danger and so everything has been done to obfuscate their whereabouts. Even within our leadership, no one Harper is aware of more than one or two of them. Those that were known have been arranged to live ordinary lives of no importance so as to be beneath the notice of those who might seek to use them in some gambit to bring back their Lord Father. By living boring normal lives, perhaps they will escape the chaotic fate that prophecy has dictated of them.

We must be committed to the prevention of Alaundo's prophecy by any means we can. While some believe we must take a more active role, Elminster believes that acting with ignorance is worse than not acting at all, and we still know so little. If you come unto the identity of any of them, reveal it to no one else and do not risk drawing attention to them by attempting to make contact. We who Harp must always exercise discretion on when to sing, and when to stay silent.~
@6746=~The Rise of the Black Sun~
@6747=~It was a ruinous providence indeed that the mortal Cyric ascended with not just one portfolio from the Dead Three in his grasp, but all three. He did not rest on his laurels. Those who had worshipped Bane, Bhaal, and Myrkul previously rushed to swear themselves to the Black Sun, for how could they resist the power of this new god, who embodied everything their old masters had and so much more? Those who remained obstinate in their old allegiances were predictably given no mercy, snuffed away in their old houses of worship.  

Cyric has since been proactive with stamping out remnants of the old gods of his domains. Mausoleums dedicated to Myrkul have been defaced and icons to the Black Sun put in their place. The old iron edifices of Bane's rule have been knocked on their side and turned to madhouses. In those hidden altars of bloody sacrifice, Bhaal's serrated daggers have been replaced with skull laden shortblades more suitable to Cyric. 

What then of the progeny of Bane and Bhaal who still remain? 

Cyric has been curiously restrained with either. Iyachtu Xvim still remains missing, and perhaps Cyric is behind whatever banishment the progeny of Bane is under. Cyric is similarly uninvolved with the Bhaalspawn, giving no direction to his followers in regards to them at all. Would he not wish these last remnants stamped out with the same fervor as Bhaal's cults and temples? So far, the answer seems to be not. Perhaps then he watches from afar, waiting to see how their development can be turned to his own advantage.~
@6748=~A Reexamination of Alaundo's Prophecy~
@6749=~There have been many interpretations of Alaundo's prophecy regarding the Bhaalspawn throughout the years. Most scholars agree that the great machinations of Bhaal were some intention for his sired offspring to bring about his revival, confirmed by other less eminent prophets. In light of new information, we must re-examine the prophecy and decipher just how the mechanism of Bhaal's return is intended.

The answer would seem obvious at first. The Lord of Murder's rebirth must certainly be by murder itself? Yet this presents a question. Are his children intended to be murdered to bring about his return, or are they intended to accrue murders of their own that might emulate their father? Or both?

In our recent raid on the temple, it seemed that the cultists of Bhaal intended to put all Bhaalspawn they had gathered to the blade as soon as Bhaal had been destroyed. Yet this violates the prophecy in one key way: it states that the Bhaal children would be the source of chaos, that it would come from their passage. Perhaps then the Cult had selected one or a few children among the score to nurture, while the others would be fed to the sacrificial blade to give them strength. Yet even this seems wrong, for the prophecy refers to numerous Spawn who would be the source of chaos, and not only a few. Did the Cult get it wrong? Of all the Bhaal priests we have interrogated, none seem to have been given a full view of the exact mechanism that would bring about the revival of their Lord. In fact, the High Priest was the one tasked with conducting the rites, yet she seems to have died in the great culling from the ritual in Tantras.

Should we assume Alaundo himself was mistaken? Or is there a missing variable not yet known? A break in the link between Bhaal and his followers that has caused such a confused response to his plans? Candlekeep will be a suitable place to continue my study. And I think to raise my new charges as well.

-Gorion~
@6750=~Dossier: Amelyssan the Blackhearted~
@6751=~Race: Human
Birth: Estimated 1330
Skin: Fair
Hair: Auburn, often colored deeper red
Eyes: Blue
Other Defining Features: Observed to adorn herself in Dove feathers streaked with blood.
Rank: High Deathstalker
Death: 1357 (recorded)

There is exceedingly little information available about the Last High Deathstalker of Bhaal, known as Amelyssan the Blackhearted. Her involvement in the Cult of Bhaal must have come early in life, as she ascended to the position of High Deathstalker at a remarkably young age. While most of Bhaal's followers believe that their Lord preferred obvious and bloody displays from victims, Amelyssan was known for cold calculation and talent at manipulation and intrigue. Few direct murders have been associated with her, yet her presence was observed in the leadup to the Tethyrian Interregnum, and she's suspected to have been the primary mastermind in directing the chaos that caused the Ten Black Days of Eleint, one of the bloodiest periods of history in Faerûn. Her role in other incidents of extreme civil unrest and bloodshed is suspected, but not confirmed. 

It is only known that she was well favored by her god, and her word commanded any assassin she beheld who had ever uttered so much as a prayer to the Lord of Murder. 

Amelyssan was last reported operating within the Dragon Reach during the Time of Troubles. A body roughly matching her description and which held objects that proved her status as High Priest was located not far outside the city. It was drained in the same manner as all other assassins were in the great culling that was conducted by Bane and Myrkul. Her dossier has been closed and archived.~
@6752=~Report - Bhaalspawn Movement~
@6753=~My Lord,

I know that we're supposed to remain hands off with monitoring the Bhaalspawn, but I swear that something is transpiring that is of deepest concern. I have separately reached out to many colleagues and they each report that the Bhaalspawn they were aware of have all begun to migrate to the south and west. Two of these colleagues have now gone missing after deciding to investigate further and speak to their charges directly. 

I tell you, some force is compelling the Bhaalspawn to gather and any who dig deep are met with grisly fate. Could this be the sign? Do we stand on the verge of the chaos that Alaundo prophesized? Can we really afford to remain so inactive when danger looms so near?~
@7014=~Prophecy Translation~
@6754=~During the days of the Avatars, the Lord of Murder will spawn a score of mortal progeny. These offspring will be aligned good and evil, but chaos will flow through them all. When the Beast's bastard children come of age, they will bring havoc to the lands of the Sword Coast. One of these children must rise above the rest and claim their father's legacy. This inheritor will shape the history of the Sword Coast for centuries to come.

*A note below this reads*
One of the more verifiable interpretations of Alaundo's prophecies that I found within Candlekeep's halls. I have provided this copy so that it can be added to our archive and studied.
-Gorion~
@7015=~Prophecy Conjecture~
@6755=~The spawn of the Lord of Murder are fated to come into their inheritance through bloodshed and misery. It is the hope of their father that only one shall remain alive to inherit his legacy. I foresee that the children of Bhaal shall kill each other in a bloody massacre.

*A note below this reads*
Another of the dread translations I find unfortunately compelling regarding the Bhaalspawn. I have provided this copy so that it can be added to our archive and studied.
-Gorion~
@6875=~Scouting Report - Strange Statue in Trollbark Woods~
@6876=~We were tracking a pair of what appeared to be identical twins through the Trollbark woods. They proceeded with an odd funerary march that eventually outpaced us, however an hour later we found one of them within a disquieting glade. At the center of the glade a statue of two featureless figures, one with a blade or stick raised, prepared to strike the other who cowered in fear. 

The twin we found was dead at the foot of the statue, his head likely bashed in against it. A check of his inventory revealed iconography that identified him as a adherent to Bhaal. We suspect some ritual was conducted to emulate the scene within the statue. However the statue itself contained no indication it was made for any ritual purpose to Bhaal himself. No, this seems to me something far more ancient and primal.

*a set of directions below seems to be partially blotted out by spilled ink*

*Addendum Report: Among every culture from the barbarian tribes of the Spine of the World to the spirit shaman of Rashemen is the story of the first kin killing, that moment when one brother raises their sword against another and commits fratricide. Perhaps this statue is a recreation of that story from an older time.~
